Catto

Target IP: 192.168.195.139
Challenge Description: Will the catto catch the mousso...

Reconnaissance


Doing a port scan shows there are multiple ports open on the target machine.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open ports returns the result above. There is one SSH application on port 42022, and the rest are HTTP applications on other ports.

Enumeration

Port 30330: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this book-reviews web application. Right away, it mentions the web application is created using Gatsby. This web application contains articles that can be read by the users.


The article located at /minecraft contains the usernames of the different players: keralis, xisuma, zombiecleo, mumbojumbo, sabel, yvette, zahara, sybilla, marcus, tabbatha, and tabby. Maybe I can run spray them against the SSH application.


I searched for a random directory called asdasd to see how the web application handles this, and obtained the webpage above. There is one webpage shown above, which I highlighted in yellow, is suspicious.


Browsing to /new-server-config-mc directory displays the webpage above. This article contains the password WallAskCharacter305 of a private Minecraft server. Is this possibly the SSH application that is running on port 42022? Time to test it.


I copied all the usernames I found earlier in a file called usernames. The usernames I saved are shown above.

Exploitation


Using hydra, I sprayed the password WallAskCharacter305 against the usernames from the previous image and got a hit! The command I used for password spraying is hydra -L usernames -p WallAskCharacter305 ssh://192.168.195.139 -s 42022 -t 4. Now I have the credentials marcus:WallAskCharacter305.


And using the credentials, I managed to login to the SSH application on the target machine at port 42022. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user marcus, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting file with the name .bash. The content of this file is shown above. I tried to decode it from base64 and received the garbled output above. Maybe this is some sort of key? Using the command find / -name "*base64*" 2>/dev/null, I found the entry /usr/bin/base64key.


After some trial and error I managed to decrypt and obtain the plaintext SortMentionLeast269, as shown above. The private key I used for the decryption is the user's password WallAskCharacter305.


And I tried to switch to the user root using this new password and it worked. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.
